task.summary: Eliminated iterative search for depositions in "update_surface". Now implemented through np.argwhere(). 30x speed up of the "update_surface" function

Moved two most time consuming operations (unzipping a set and constructing a tuple) from 'laplace_term_rolling' to 'update_surface' 2x speedup of 'laplace_term_rolling' function Added global 'ghost_index' variable

Now sending 'ghosts' and 'ghosts_index' as parameters instead of referring to globals from all sub-functions Just moved make_tuple operation under a condition if there are newly deposited cells and it led to 8x speed up of 'update_surface'
Fixed ghosts_index and surf not attaining values from 'update_surface'

'pe_flux' is now taking an array and implemented with numexpr, 4x speed up 'make_tuple' is completely rewritten, 20x speed up 'flux_matrix' is no longer using iterator, but a stream of indices, 20x speed up 'pythagor' is no longer used, its functionality is done inside 'flux_matrix' with numexpr 'deposition' is working faster, idk lol So far the speed-ups provided by numexpr are a effectively a bit less than reported in the latest optimization. Since then numexpr.evaluate has grown from ~9 to ~11s for 100 loops test. Although, the overall computing time has decreased more that twice (from 78s to 34s) with the latest optimizations.

Introduced adapted function numexpr.re_evaluate_from_cache, that takes in already precompiled expressions, which eliminates unnecessary expression analysis on every call Tests showed, that numexpr.evaluate works best on a single core(MacBook pro i7 mid 2012). Thus all threads are set to one. Introduced Runge-Kutta 4 method for diffusion. Switched to array coordinate system
